TRIGGER WARNING: Mental Health and Suicide¶

The following project discusses the effects of mental health and suicide which some may find distrubing. If you struggle with suicidal thoughts/ideation, please call the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline at 988.¶

Analysis of How Gender and Race are Related to Deaths Caused by Suicide¶

By: Mia Ndousse-Fetter¶

Introduction:¶

Mental health has been a popular topic of conversation in recent years. Many beleive America specifically is facing a mental health crisis. This is affecting people in all ages and demographics but especially young people. According to the CDC, almost 1 in every 3 teenagers reported that they would describe their mental health as poor[1]. Additionally, the National Alliance on Mental Illness reports that suicide is the second leading cause of death for teenagers and young adults ages 15-24[1].

There are many reasons why someone may feel like they need to take their own life. Common risk factors include attachment to issues that occured in childhood, childhood trauma, developmental delays and mental health issues. Young people are said to become even more vulnerable as they are exposed to cultural messages, social media and drugs/alcohol [2]. Especially with recent events going on in this country and around the world including the recent Covid-19 pandemic, effects of global warming, increases political polarization, the wealth gap, racism, etc. makes it harder for younger people to have a positive outlook on life

Motivation and Purpose:¶

I decided to focus on the 15-24 years old age group for this project becuase I was interested in how people my age are affected by this issue. I think it's important to bring more awareness and to discuss about mental health and suicide so people feel more comfortable to reach out and find help for themselves or a loved one. Some preventable actions that can be taken are: creating a more stable home environment, reducing substance use through community based policy and practices, and engage community members in shared activites[3].

As Suicide affects people from all walks of life, I wanted to explore if one's background (race or gender) could be related to the number of suicide deaths. If we can understand the common factors of people who are affected, then more effective efforts can be done to help decrease suicidal deaths. *In this project, I will examine if there's a statistically siginificant relationship between a race/gender and suicide rate. Null Hypothesis: There is no relationship between demogrpahic (race and gender) and suicide rate.

Dataset/Data collection:¶

The data for this porject is from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services titled Death rates for Suicide, by sex, race, hispanic origin and age: United States(https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/death-rates-for-suicide-by-sex-race-hispanic-origin-and-age-united-states-020c1). Since I'm only focusing on the 15-24 age group, I only extract rows that include that age group. I start with tidying the dataset below *Note: in the dataset the number of deaths per 100,000 people is reported in the 'ESTIMATE' column. I just refer to this number as the 'rate' for the rest of this project.

Discussion on Imputations:¶

There are many NaN values for some demogrpahics. For example Native American and Alaska Native Females almost have no data from the 1950's to 1980's. Of course, for a more seamless data analysis a complete dataset is preferred which is where imputaitons come in. I do not believe any imputation method is appropriate for this dataset. Much of the missing data affects non-white racial groups from the 1950's to 1970's. This may be due to a systemic neglect of gathering data on people of color, but I do not have enough information to substantiate that claim.This fits Missingness Completely as Random as the missing values aren't related to any other patterns in the data. Most traditional imputation methods such as MICE assume Missing at Random which is not the case for this data. I don't feel comfortable doing a single imputation because there is missing data for many consecutive years in most cases. That is why I ultimately decided to drop the Nan values present in the dataset as seen below.

Again, the Male group has the highest rate irrespective of race. Let's see if this relatiionship between gender and suicide rate is statistically signifcant using an Ordinary Least Squares Regression Model from the statsmodels library

In [168]:
#now want to explore if theres a statistically significant relationship between gender and death rate using OLS regression
import statsmodels.formula.api as sm
#adding an interaction between gender
reg = sm.ols(formula="Rate ~ Year: Gender", data=result4).fit()
print(reg.summary())

Discussion on whether gender is statistically signifcant when compared to the suicide rate¶

In the scatterplot of all data points, boxplot and line plot of the average per year by gender, men had the highest rates. To examine the statistical siginifcance of this relationship I ran a the Ordinary Least Squares Regression alogrithm. An interaction term for Gender was added to get results from every category: all genders, female, and male. Looking at the report above, the p values are 0.016, 0.026, and 0.010 for all genders, female, and male respectively. All of these values are less than 0.05 which is the standard threshold to determine statistical significance. Thus, we can reject the null hypothesis and assume that gender does play a role in sucide rate and that men seem to be affected more than the other gender groups.

Discussion on whether race affects suicide rate over time¶

The p-values of all races (0.999), America Indian or Alaska Native (0.796), Asian or Pacific Islander (0.949), Black or African American (0.948), Hispanic or Latino (0.947), and white (0.987) are all over the alpha threshold of 0.05. The means that race is not statistically signifcant for suicide rate. These results surprised me because people of color face more systemic racism and inequality, which I thought would translate in worse mental heath and a higher suicide rate. However, this is not enough information to assert that race has absolutely no bearing on suicide rate. Other factors that are not inlcuded in this dataset like income and access to mental health should be analyzed. Since this dataset also include the gender, I will see if gender and race are statistically siginifcant for suicide rate in the next section.

Polynomial regression for gender and race groups¶

I will now break up the scatterplot to visualize the data between one gender and one race. Next a polynomial regression line to the 4th degress will be fitted to each graph. The reason why I chose a polynomial to the 4th degree is because of the high r values associated with each graph. These r values for each category are printed and they are all at or higher than 0.5. For the social sciences that is considered very strong [4] and shows a high level of correlation between our data and polynomial line of best fit. This is an indication that the polymoial regression of the 4th degree is a good fit. Other degree values like 1,2, and 3 were tried, but they all had lower results.

After plotting these graphs, statsmodels regression is used for our polynomial model to give us some more statistical insights

In [300]:
#scatter plot for every race and gender
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
#grouping by gender and race
for i, group in result4.groupby(['Gender', 'Race']):
    plt.figure()
    #setting x andy variables to be used
    x=group['Year']
    y=group['Rate']
    #fitting polynomial to 4 degree
    z = np.poly1d(np.polyfit(x,y,4))
    #this sets the range of the polynomial line of best fit to be the time period of our data (1950-2018)
    line = np.linspace(1950, 2018, 100)
    #labeling title and axes
    plt.title(i)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Rate')
    #plotting scatter 
    plt.scatter(x,y)
    #plotting line
    plt.plot(line, z(line))
    #printing r-squared values
    print(i,'r-squared= ', r2_score(y, z(x)))

Discussion of Statsmodels results¶

For almost every p-value is 0, except for American Indians for all genders. Because this is lower than the standard alpha threshold of 0.05, this shows that for every other gender and race combination, there is a statistically significant relationship between that specific race and gender category and suicide rate (We can reject null hypothesisn that there's no relationship). Overall each year, the suicide rate increases for specific gender and race combinations (this is from looking at the coefficent column). The highest increase is with American Indian or Alaskan Natives with a 2.8485 increase every year. The higest increase for women was also the American Indian or Alaskan Native group. All of the male racial groups had a higher rate than the women in their racial group, giving more evidence to the idea that higher rates of suicde are present in men.

Wrap-Up and Discussion¶

The key finds of the data analysis show that men have higher rates of suicide than women across all racial groups. The statistical significance of this was proved by looking at p-values and seeing that all of them first individual racial and gender groups were zero. We saw that race by itself did not have a statistically signifcant relationship but gender did, with men irregardless of rates had higher rates overall and yearly. Another finding was that Native Americans for both genders had the highest yearly incrase in suicide rate.

I would like to emphasize that there are so many other factors that contribute to someone's overall decline in mental health that weren't included in this dataset. Things like access to resources and community support are so vital to preventing suicide. This dataset and analysis alone isn't enough evidence fully to make concrete claims about the causes of suicide. However the findings that were mentioned in the above paragrpah can open discussion and further analysis to why certain groups are affected over others. For example, causes of higher rates of male suicide can be studied and resources can be put into more programs speicalized in helping the mental health of men. Higher rates of male suicide has been studied before and is called the "suicide gap" between genders. This phenomenon is observed in many other countries as well. [5]

If were to expand this project, I think it would be interesting to introduce other age groups and see how they compare with one another. Do men have the highest rate for all gender and age groups? Insights from that analysis would be valuable to explore so we can exmaine the possible causes and how they may be different for different ages.
